Need for Speed: The Run races across America.
Review
The initially carefree ride, due to a series of completely unnecessary lajatry errors, turns into a routine morning ride on the shift.
The ambition has been largely fulfilled, but it is no avail it to make no difference when no one seems to want to do anything extra.
The new episode, subtitled The Run, attracted high expectations before it was released.
He promised to move the age-old Need for Speed racing series again in a new direction, appearing from playable previews as a game that might not only be in the number in the field of action racing.
We were also curious to see how the inserted passages would turn out, in which the main character would get out of the car and run his own way.
But, as is customary for the NFS series, much is a bit different in the end than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole draws down some unnecessary mistakes that have been appearing in the series for more or less for several years.
So it's not really even mistakes, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are inducted into a story whose main character, Jack, has some personal problems and is offered as a solution to participate in an illegal race across America.
Behind the wheel, you get on the West Coast in San Francisco, and your job is to arrive first in New York.
The idea entails some interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is run on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
It doesn't feel like the game's always the same thing.
In addition, some of the backgrounds are very nice to look at, even though the technical level of the graphics is consistent with the previous parts of the series.
So it's not a big deal.
But driving across the desert, the autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains feels visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are made up of some atypical element from time to time.
In the desert, for example, you get stuck in a sandstorm that reduces visibility considerably.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be careful not to be caught by an avalanche.
Alongside this, the individual races are pretty well in a row.
There are only a few types of them, but that's enough.
For a while you try to overtake the required number of opponents (basically a classic race), then catch up again (the classic duel with the stopwatch) and then there is a duel with a single opponent waiting for you.
This is what the police get involved from time to time, making your whole effort even further unpleasant.
The new feature is the passages outside the car.
It's more of an interactive animation, when Jack usually flees from someone and you have to help him do it by printing the right buttons in the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
But it is surprising that there are far fewer of these passages in the game than you would have expected (specifically, perhaps only three).
In the end, however, it is to the benefit of the cause, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and, in the context of the above, thus ranks among the elements that enhance the game.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of previous episodes.
That means it's definitely not something these days, but you can't say he's a mess.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But the more accurately conceptual racing of the driving model here still fits quite well, even though we could find a better one for the competition.
So far, so to speak, everything in perfect order.
But problems are starting to emerge after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not very well.
We don't expect a game of this type to count the complex deformities and collisions, but when you have no idea before any crash to any object how your car will behave, then I guess everything is not quite right.
Typically, when you're overtaking or passing cars in normal traffic, you can sometimes just latch each other, but at other times in an almost identical situation your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even to fuck off.
The reboots system doesn't particularly matter, but it will make you feel good.
The reboggarts are designed so that if you smash or go far out of the track, the game will throw you back to the last clue on the track.
But only five reboots are available in each race.
If you exhaust them, you have to start the race again from the beginning.
It is, therefore, more of a tool in case something goes wrong than to be able to rely on them in a downright way.
But sometimes even the reboots don't help, solving them only when the need to learn the given section of the race from memory.
The big ailment of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some corners, for example, need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply won't fit into them.
At other times, you will always meet "civil" cars at the site in the same configuration, whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
It will be annoyed especially in situations where you see the opponent driving in front of you between the two oncoming cars, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around them or brake them.
It doesn't matter when you reach them, because it's "calculated" so that the situation is always just in front of your nose.
The rivals also have another advantage.
Throughout the game you will come across a few places where, again, regardless of time, you are always overtted by the same opponent in the same place.
It hits the most at the end of the game on a long bridge, where you're going in the opposite direction.
The opponent must obviously get there in front of you at any price.
When he rides ahead of you, it worsens your insight into oncoming cars, so you probably get a nice little bit there at first.
It is possible to understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-fuelled, but the design is so obvious that it will reliably quickly disgust you.
And it's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and, in places, action so much that sometimes you literally can't keep track of where what flies.
And it doesn't really matter whether the credited to the concept with the fifty unique tracks, the gearshift of the races so that boredom doesn't have a chance or anything else.
The unconventional idea is to replace cars during the races.
You have to be careful of the gas stations by the roads, because that's where you can change the car, even though in the vast majority of cases you can make do with what you have right now.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports are suitable for urban areas, heavy American highway crashs, and exotic supersports for technical riding, such as winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand with the challenge mode, which are the races in the individual locations you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points in your profile, which is common for challenges and a story.
For obtaining a higher level of driver, different items are unlocked: from the cars to the background for the profile.
It is also again linked to the online feature of Autolog, which, among other things, compares your achieved results with other players and provides additional community functions.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation of the last race in the story.
With your car you will get to the subway tunnel (so be so), where you are in the dark to whiten down the tracks (see).
The speedometer is flashing the numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (let me) and in that there will be a subway train coming from behind and uncompromisingly scrapping you.
In the newsroom, we will probably still have to spend a few more days discussing whether no one really thought a little bit when creating the play, or whether the authors think of us as really such a big jerk.
The technical side of the game is not a big one, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and, in a few cases, even great.
It freezes in the fact that in some of the more tense imaging drops, in some cases quite tragically.
But it mainly concerns crashes with more participants, when seamless imaging would no longer do you any good.
The sound side is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an attempt to appeal to the widest range of rather younger audiences, the soundtrack from the category of "every dog a different village" was created, but it can be assumed that, because of listening to music, someone will probably not buy the game.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so highly embarrassed.
If the game were to avoid completely unnecessary errors, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best part of the NFS in the last few years.
This is how the game feels unfinished.
