How tour prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia at the time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agents at the time were overwhelmingly selling only trips to the socialist bloc countries, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists thus travelled on holiday to the sea to the GDR (the German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea by the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (the Balathon).
The bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when there was a chance to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime went to the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to, for example, Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise an individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered tours to the West, but you needed to queue up overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who were thus unable to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without the foreign exchange promise it was not possible to raise funds (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
However, the most frequently spent Czechs vacationing in the Czech Republic, resulting in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs purchased and this custom survives to this day.
The travel of the Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in the countries around the world.
The huge paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to us for the most popular Croatia to date in 1989, as it was part of what was then Yugoslavia.
Early in the 1990s, visa requirements were lifted to neighbouring Western European countries, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits to Austria's Vienna or Germany in particular.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to at least take a moment to see it.
In Paris, for example, the tours of Czechs in parks in tents were sleeping, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a guesthouse.
A typical feature of Czechs' travel at this time was to drive their own food, preserves, salami, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, which our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely after many weeks of years.
However, our standard of living standards and, with it, average salaries were rising, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to regularly prepare tours with charter air links since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs already had visa-free travel to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the US, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came as soon as 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the first direct charter flight to exotica was dispatched from the Czech Republic, to Thailand.
