The quintet has included the country in its tour to celebrate 20 years of existence
"The trip to Costa Rica is a dream that becomes reality"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band was ready to offer one of the best gigs at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have waited more than 20 years, but the group itself assures that the opportunity for them to play in Costa Rica represents a dream come true.
This is what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively to Viva from Brazil last week, said.
The group is on the South American continent as part of a tour to celebrate 20 years of existence and will be at a unique stop in Central America on Sunday 20th.
This day will be performed at the National Stadium from 7:30 p.m. with the angel band The X and the national musicians of Las Robertas.
This is a sample from the interview, the entire transcript of which can be found on the website of La Nación on the internet.
For your Costa Rican supporters, it's a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
The journey to Costa Rica is also our dream, which is becoming a reality.
In South and Central America, we've barely been the second and experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on holiday. It's a beautiful country, and I believe we can stay here for a few days.
So we're so happy to bring you our music.
I ask because they literally adore the group here, the fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensively.
What do you say to your most terrible supporters?
Thank you for standing by us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to reach Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people already refer to the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that give you more pressure?
Some of the biggest shows we've put on in the last 21 years have been made within a few weeks.
We have put on some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope to get into shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
In fact, we're really looking forward to the concert.
We love this country, we like to surf, we like to enjoy the jungles. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves to surf?
We have a lot of surfer friends, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go to surf in Costa Rica or Nicaragua, or Mexico. These are the best surfing spots. And so we found out about Costa Rica, through people who love to surf.
If you look at your tour, you've prepared a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan to present in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we have no limitations on what we can't do.
We will try to put on the best show with a variety of tracks. We will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What for?
I think in part it's because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 tracks and everyone likes different tracks, so it's hard to choose what songs we'll play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven't played for a long time, we focus on them and we're also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that maybe we've forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting for us, which is why I think it is more interesting for the people as well.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of artistic career.
When you look back, is it hard to believe everything you've accomplished?
Yes, I'm sure.
First of all, I think that none of us could have imagined that we would be in one big rock band and that we would stay in it for more than 20 years. Sounds like a dream.
We realise how much we have been given and are touched by the fact that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and like making music.
We are lucky to be able to look at the places we've always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honour for us to be a part of this group in which the great greats are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It's surprising when a movement emerges from a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
A group will be formed from time to time in the city, but it is far less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at once.
We are proud of this and we are honoured to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play with some of them.
Last year we went to the Alice in Chains festival and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are fortunate to be all our friends and we are honoured to be part of this movement that was formed in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a much longer time than the usual duration of the group.
I think, first of all, we are all fortunate to be still in this world and secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends, and as a result, we have managed to open up musical paths that leave everyone with sufficient freedom to experiment themselves.
We trust each other, we respect each other's music, and I don't think it could be better.
Your relationship to the word fame was not easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find the balance?
The way we grew, it was gradually getting easier to find a balance.
We try not to go too much on tour because it's very easy to fall into this trap of the crowds and the people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for the music, you remind yourself that you have to respect the music and what you've given it. You mustn't get carried away by being famous, rock stars. This was never really of interest to either of us.
How do you remember another Mother Love Bone project?
I think we were writing great songs and it was something spectacular at the beginning.
As a band, we existed for three years and we never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. Most importantly, even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at the photos, I remember Andy, how unbelievable he was, how I laughed at him. It was always a joy to work with him, to laugh, to talk about music or football and much more.
She was an incredible person and we miss her.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to launch a show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as the opening actuators?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several designs, and we liked this group the most. That's why we're curious to see what Las Robertas will offer live and they need to be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he adds the first thing he can think of.
Who is affecting you as a bassist?
Lots of people.
First up, I'm first thought of Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many of them, I could talk all night about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to hold on to grunge, even though it is no longer in vogue?
I think we've all always felt a little separated from the word grunge.
When you say grunge, I imagine the groups I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that were created at the same time. And if music is still this valid today, it's something great because it's the music that's worth listening to and the likes of Mudhoney players are playing better music today than ever before.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly grim character and is now more positive.
What is behind this change?
That's interesting because I feel like there are a few songs in the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe, which are considered very grim, although they may come off as positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they're songs deeply dark.
I think when you grow up and you have some trauma in your life, you lose someone from a family or a friend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
