Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized on Tuesday at a public hospital to give him tests for the muscle loss he has suffered in the lower limbs, his treating physician reported.
Fujimori, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights abuses by his government (1990-07) suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated on four times and is already under control by doctors.
MP Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told the TV station Canal N that Fujimori would undergo tests at the National Institute of Discral Diseases in three days, where they should find out why he is hurting and why he is losing strength in his lower extremities.
Aguinaga said that in his view Fujimori might be pardoned on humanitarian grounds, but the former president himself does not want a pardon because he feels innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and these problems were added by other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, a pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, high pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been serving a sentence since September 2007 at the National Headquarters of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people who were killed by a murdering squadron of troops operating illegally in the early years of his reign.
