Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has launched research into the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for obesity for children and adolescents. Research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to detect the obesity gene in children and the young. Research called "Abre Obesity Genetics in Children and Teentism" will make it possible to obtain overweight results.
In a report by the head of the Biochemistry Research Medical Unit at the Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century National Health Center, Miguel Cruz López, he explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team relies on the support of specialists and pupils of postgraduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and from the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Institute of Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research can also involve the general public, with or not authorized. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where they will take tests to minors each reindeer from 8 a.m.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexican State) and from 8. October, this activity is also carried out at the Unlandalcóyolt Sports Centre (East of the Mexican State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children have been obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Moreloses Sports Centre (north of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research was to identify the components and importance of genetics when it comes to developing obesity and to trace to Mexican children and young people risk factors and thus prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the age of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about the physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, all participants are given anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), the blood pressure is measured, glucose levels, triglicerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined and genes are studied (he is to be able to identify the genes involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said the research reflected the alarm of health professionals' alarming rise in the child's weight.
'Health polls conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was an increase in obesity in boys by 77% and for girls by 47%. There was also a dramatic increase in the case of overweight, said the IMSS expert.
He said that one of the reasons for the search for indicators was to suggest that the country's population differed from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% of Indian-American genetic make-up, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in the genes responsible for the emergence of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, obesity genetics is commonly explained as an inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calorie) and stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they will receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, to determine whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He said that even the presence of dark-coloured wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearms suggests the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-trick cells.
The information is confidential so far, with doctors handing it over to their parents in writing and explaining to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make to avoid the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three major ingredients that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day, and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
Overweight is also due to a large caloric intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content, and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
In Asphalt from UNAM there will be no potholes
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the Chemical Faculty of the UNAM, creates modified asphalts with polymers to create a mixture with better functionality, independently of climatic conditions and temperature
If the cobbles were properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each rainy season at the Metropolitan area of Valle de México, Rafael Herrera Niner, a scientist at the Chemical Faculty (FQ) at the ANC, who also added that if the design and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or even be able to be removed altogether.
In his lecture, the Technology Cause of Colour, he said in the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership was developing modified asphalts with polymers, creating a mixture with similar characteristics to the asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the creation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the hardest part of the oil, is a cluster of hydrocarbon molecules, moocclesiles with a large molecular mass called asphalten, and others with low molecular weights called mortars. Together, they give the asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoleastic character of the asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it acts like a liquid, has a high viscosity at 120 degrees and is almost in firm state at 50 degrees, while at low temperatures asphalt has a tendency to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperatures, the chemical engineering expert pointed out.
A scientist from the Chemistry School observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible paving, which consists of six layers of materials, the last of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers are the asphalt insert, made up of small stones topped in the asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that forms the liner is topped with asphalt.
When passing through cars or when you create pressure, it is possible to disinheritate the forces in the pavement well.
If it was modified asphalt, they would be disassembled even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the asphalt insert is the last layer called a cloak, made up of fine rock, i.e. sand also cloudy in asphalt.
As this layer will come into contact with the vehicle rims, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the road.
As part of the cobbles, it will be subject to heavy loads, the casing must be of sufficient thickness and be watched for the material from which it is made.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to be remembered. In particular, the water has a great effect on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is damp, the water travels inwards and it's hard to get out, it causes all layers of the tile to soften up the pile and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that the film of the cape was first damaged during the creation of potholes, and afterwards, the asphalt insert was damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one point, but it is a gradual process that should stop at the first signs using the appropriate maintenance programmes.
As a member of the National Researcher System, he also explained that the load on vehicles is another important factor in creating potholes, and therefore the thickness of each single layer of the pile must be commensurate with the load of vehicles and it must be guaranteed that this burden will not be exceeded. Only in this way can we prevent the frequent emergence of potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there is still a lot of work to do when it comes to asphalt, and the research is at the beginning. It is worth noting, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and make it easy to repair potholes without having to use high temperatures.
