The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The undersea pipe is made of steel fitted with a concrete casing to be protected from the moorings of the naval vessels.
It is at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
In its construction, it was necessary to avoid the minefields from the time of the Second World War.
"Because of safety, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase the measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipes themselves are a long metal snake weighing like the 242 Eiffel Tower, which is not interrupted anywhere by the valves or maintenance stations.
